< username>
Geneva Murray<//username>
<Pics>None<//Pics><Rating>5</Rating>< Review>
I love this park. It has big open fields for flying kites or volleyball or soccer. It also has basketball courts, a nice playground, and lots of swings. The best part is that the baby swings are in the shade during the hotter hours.

I almost forgot the water park! It's on an automatic timer that starts every 10 minutes and the park is open for all of the hot months.

This park is fantastic.</Review>

1529697607336<//Time>
<Rating>3</Rating>< Review>
This park is good to spend time as a family. This park has a BBQ area, water area for the kids to get wet and have lots of fun in, a play area with slides and swings, lots of grass to play in, and places to sit while you enjoy watching your kids have fun. The cons of this park there is no bathrooms, the place is a bit rundown, and spray paint on some of the equipment. But if you can overlook those this is a fun park.

If this is not the park for you there is a better park with a water area in Olivehurst called Eufey Wood Spray Park.</Review>

< Text>
Came here to do a joint massage with my sister. This is one of the more expensive places to get a massage ($125 for a 60 min standard therapeutic massage), but Donna was amazing. When I arrived, she looked at me and said my body was a bit twisted (I couldn't tell, but I had been feeling pretty beaten up after 3 months of nursing my baby). She used a blend of different techniques on me and I left feeling like a new person. In general the entire facility is very soothing and well-appointed; the decor seems to be a blend of tasteful Asian and Moroccan elements. Before our massages, we were offered a light refreshing tea (peach mint, if I remember correctly), and afterwards we were given water. There is a reception room where one can relax before or after appointments, and it has spa water and healthy snacks with magazines to read. The only minor hitch during my visit was when I noticed some stains on the cloth that lined the face pillow. I was told it was from past clientele's mascara rubbing off and that doesn't really come off anymore in the wash. However the cloth was promptly replaced with an unstained one so it wasn't a big deal. Overall I had a great experience here.<//Text>

< Text>
I just left Avant Gard and burst into tears after having my eyebrows done.  Months of growing my eyebrows out to have the modern look of a straighter/low arch was just waxed away in 15 minutes.

Last month I had my first ever eyebrow shaping and wax with Lauren. She did a fantastic job and we had a plan to grow and shape my brows the way I stated above.  When I went in today, I expected Lauren to just clean up my brows and continue working on growing and shaping.  I was shocked when I looked in the mirror to see that Lauren had waxed my eyebrow hairs and given me arches!  I guess I should have restated to Lauren what we had gone over previously.  I thought they kept notes on individual clients much like colonists but apparently not.  Now my beautiful thick eyebrows are thinned out and arched and will take months to grow out.

Avant Gard comped my appointment and I left Lauren a tip but I am very upset about what happened.  I spoke to Christine, the front desk manager, and she was very sweet and offered to have a make-up specialist how to deal with my eyebrows, but I declined.  I even cancelled my massage for Saturday because I am so upset about what happened.</Text>

I came here with a friend about 30 minutes to closing. They let us come in and we ordered the strawberry and tiramisu souffle. Inside is pretty small, but super cute with pink walls. They made them really fast and we left to eat outside. The souffles were really fluffy and tasty as well. However, I think they were a bit too sweet than I had anticipated. The sauce it came with was definitely too sweet for me. While we had gotten our own, I think these can definitely be shared. I would probably come back, but the souffles were really sweet.< /review>

<review>I came across Uni Souffle on Yelp and HAD to try it. So, we made a plan and drove to Milbrae specifically to try them out. We ordered the Pink Unicorn tea, which was super good, and another mango/strawberry (Sunset maybe?) tea, that I really enjoyed as well. Now, on to the souffles. They weren't quite what I was expecting, way fluffier, and way more egg-like than I thought they would be. We shared the strawberry and the cookies and cream, and the four of us (2 adults, 2 kids) didn't come close to finishing them. It's a lot. Delicious, but really rich and sweet. We decided we'd go back when we're in the neighborhood to try different flavors of both the teas and souffles. All in all, a fun little adventure for a super tasty treat!<//review>< pictures>

<Rate>5</Rate>< Text>
I have been at this establishment several times! However, it was few years ago, when I used live in the area of Cal Poly Pomona. It is a nice Chinese restaurant. The meals, inside, usually are delicious. There is a good amount of meals to choose from. Furthermore, this place is similar to Panda Express. However, unlike Panda Express, their portions are quite larger. At the same time, the prices are quite fair. So definitely, if anyone is in the area of City of Industry, I would recommend to stop by this restaurant!<//Text>

<username>Carl Valdez<//username><user_id>115330397538969991649</user_id><text>This is mobile pizza made from a truck.  There is no brick n mortar restaurant that cooks the pizza - so it comes quick.  You can only get it delivered.  As for the food - actually pretty good.  We had the Tom B Good, a sausage and pepperoni pizza. Very flavorful,  with roasted garlic. Crust was decent. Salad was the freshest in a package I've had. Very fresh.  Good veggies. For the packaging of the pizza, they use a special compostable material that neither gets on your pizza as well as is 100% biodegradable.  This is the future of food deliveries.</text>< Response>

< text>
We ordered this pizza to a park since we wanted to try it and we're out of the delivery zone. We ordered on the website on the way there, and it arrived before we did! I think it was about 11 minutes from order to dinner. The experience was fun, and the pizza was better than expected. Not soggy, maybe a tad salty, but overall enjoyable. The packaging is cool. <name>Joshua Lowitz<//name>< date>
1536807446489< /date>
<rate>2<//rate>< text>
Not impressed. First off the Android app doesn't work - got an error message at every screen. I ordered through the website instead. Second - kind of pricey - $23 after delivery fee for a basic pepperoni pizza.  Third - these robots might be impressive to watch on YouTube promo videos, but they aren't fast. I placed my order at 6:13 and the estimated delivery window was 40-55 minutes. Pizza actually arrived at 7:19 (64 minutes). The pizza comes in a "pod" - a stylish, compostable, biodegradable container, so at least there's that.  As for the pizza itself - it honestly isn't very good. For these prices it should be much better. The crust was more tough than chewy and had a slightly dried out stale texture like reheated leftover pizza. I usually love the outside crust on pizza and happily consume my wife and kids' scraps - but here it was so tough it hurt my jaw.  The cheese and pepperoni were both kind of bland. Unfortunately there aren't a lot of great pizza places in the South Bay, but at these prices I would rather go to a place like Amicis, Doppio Zero, hell - even CPK usually has better pizza.  For mediocre quality pizza,  this honestly is not much better than Domino's $5 2-topping special (which is also much faster).< /text>

I called there customer service number to attempt to correct the issue but rather than taking my order over the phone to allow me to move on with my plans for the evening or attempting to offer us something to keep our business, the rep walked me through a standard "IT help desk" experience, asking what browser I was using, requesting that I take a screenshot and email it to her, etc. To say the least, this was a frustrating and overall unsatisfying experience. I certainly won't try this again an would not recommend it to others.

As a side note, I took a second to debug the issue, and by simply pulling up the Chrome networking tools, I could see that their "register" request was returning a "phone must me a string" error in the response payload. This pretty clearly look like a bug in the application.<//review>

<date>1549347464288<//date><Rate>3<//Rate>< text>
UPDATE:  Last 2 pies I tried were... okay.  Still not great, though.  Kinda bland, with gloppy cheese. I swear, Zume Pizza and I are like the football and Charlie Brown.  I remain so optimistic, so hopeful... but keep getting disappointed :(.

---

Zume's delivery and customer service have always been OUTSTANDING, but unfortunately the tastiness of their pies has been highly variable.

I ordered two pies today, and I'd rate them a 2 out of 5 for texture and flavor :(.  Soggy, mushy, floppy, no perceptible sauce at all, felt vastly undercooked.  The toppings themselves are fine... crisp, flavorful, but everything else... not so much :-(.

I hope Zume can get things straightened out.  I applaud the company's innovative approach and am especially delighted by their no-tipping stance (whoa, paying workers a decent wage? Nice!).  And as noted, Zume's delivery and customer service staff have been super-quick, friendly, just all-'round awesome.

But in the end, it's really about the pies.  And most sadly, I plan on throwing out both of the pies I got today and just picking up Safeway's "Open Nature" pizzas for $5 each in their place.</text>

<rate>3</rate><Text>Ordered 3 pizzas, drinks and cookies online for delivery.

Delivery:
-Pizza arrived well within the time frame.
-Text messages all arrived at the same time so that is a glitch ("on it's way, almost there, and delivered" texts all came at the same exact time when it was delivered)
-Well packaged, all three pizzas where in 1 foil insulated bag that was sealed and you get to keep (was surprised on that) driver also had one of those pizza bags.
-One thing the delivery driver said was there was no way to know what the customer ordered, so he basically said hope this is right. (not rating on this, just that it should probably be addressed.)

Pizza:
Ordered Cheese, pepperoni, and veggie
-They where all just above room temp warm, not hot not cold... big surprise since I saw the guy take them out of one of those typical pizza bags AND they came in one of those foil bags...
-Toppings looked evenly spread out
-Had to cut the pizzas again even thought they looked to be cut already...
-Tasted below average, I have had better frozen pizzas that where about the same in cost but for delivery it wasn't too bad for just the $10 cheese and $10 pepperoni but almost $18 for the simple veggie was pushing it.
-Don't know what type of cooking method they use but it is as inconstant as can be to the point I would assume it was microwaved, but  the thing is I've had microwaved frozen pizzas that came out the same every time... All three pizzas had crust that was cooked different, one was chewy one was too crispy, and one was almost not baked enough... I thought "robots" would be more consistent than this.
-Crust wasn't anything special either, tasted like it was there because it had to be lol...
-Cheese would not stick to the pizza making me think that these pizzas never got hot enough in the first place to fully melt and "bond" the cheese.

Cookies:
-Would have been perfect if they weren't so heavily salted... Even McD don't salt their fries as much as these chocolate chip cookies were salted, heck margaritas have less salt on the glass than these lol... Once I brushed some of the salt off it was very enjoyable and was perfectly salted at that point. Must had just been the ones I had or something.

Drinks:
-Boylan Cane Cola was very good and cold
-Hubert's Lemonade was cold but not so great, may have been because it was about to expire the day I got my order...

Overall:
Really it's 2.5 stars not 3.
Not great but not bad but not average either, probably would not order again. The cheese, toppings and sauce are pretty good but how the crust was cooked different on three pizzas and the overall low temperature of the pizzas (which is surprising given how well it was packaged to keep heat in) and having to cut it again, made it not great in taste and experience nor is it worth the cost at this point.

Almost think if I had put it in my oven and baked it longer it would have been better and maybe 3.5 star pizza, but at that point why not cook a frozen pizza. Looking at other reviews the temperature and "non stick" cheese have been issues before. I think for now I will stick with "human made" or frozen pizza and stay away from "robot made" for now. Zume in general, I think advertising is overly done and made too much hype for this. May revisit but wont be for a while to see if anything has changed.</Text><Pics>None< /Pics><response>None</response><gmapID>0x808fb0b4d373bb9f:0x5a8a4bc21cd9ff0b< /gmapID></record>

< Text>
We just had our first order.  Let me start by saying that all the reviews that say the pizza was soggy please take with a grain of salt.  Also, the reviews that say the pizza was too salty, they probably took the grain of salt :) . Both our pizzas were fine.  The box is designed to keep moisture away from the pizza as opposed to the standard cardboard box.  My Papa John pizza is way more soggy, in the middle, than this was.  Actually any delivery pizza has been way more soggy in the middle.  Now to the pizzas, we ordered Sonrisa (With the gluten thank you) and Sweet Corn Elote.  I like the Sweet Corn Elote and the wife liked the Sonrisa.  We were aware that we are not ordering traditional pizzas so we were open to new tastes.  And these certainly were new.  Will definitely order again to try out some of the other pizzas.  But if ordering for a birthday party, I am getting the traditional pizza from somewhere else because you have to give the guests what they expect.< /Text>

< Text>
Lets first talk about the cost of a carrier screening. I was referred to this company by my wife's doctor, since she's pregnant. They stated that they had a 'special' rate of $199. Upon receiving the kit and calling support, they first asked for my insurance info. I explained that I would be paying via credit card and do not want my insurance involved. For curiosity, I asked, "what would be the cost billed to my insurance if you did send it to them?" Answer: $1,672! Well, my deductible is over $2,000 so had I just gone along and provided my insurance info, I would be hit with a $1,672 bill. Seriously? "Cash" option defaults to $649, but if you pay within 30 days, the cost is 'just' $349. Although I had preemptively contacted them to discuss their discounted rate, I still receive a bill for $349.

Given these fees, one would expect that this screening would be considered a diagnostic test, but upon my surprise, the results form clearly states "Carrier screening is not diagnostic and may not detect all possible pathogenic variants in a given gene". Wonderful.

To top it all off, they send out a contracted phlebotomist collect the blood. I am perfectly fine with pain and needles, but when said phlebotomist inserted the needle into my vein, I felt painful surge of lighting down my forearm. I calmed exclaimed, "I think you've hit a nerve". Phlebotomist lazily replies, "That's your vein" and proceeds to swap out the vial to fill a second one and in that process digs that needle even deeper into the vein. It took all my strength not to scream out.

I have never had an experience like this in my life. I continued to have "electrifying" pains down my arm for the remainder of that day and they still continue. I sent an email to Natera on the day of the blood draw, over two weeks ago, and have yet to have received a reply. I have since had to pay out of my pocket to visit a neurologist to assess the damage... all this because I just want to make sure my baby will be healthy.

If you have other options, please seek them. My experience was an amazing disappointment and could end up having lastly medical implications.</Text>

< Review>
The view does not disappoint after only a short hike from parking lot 1, or the northern most lot. Paths are mostly paved, and can be done with a stroller. Just be aware that there are hills, especially if going down to the beach. Also, the last bit to the observation platform does have stairs, and steep drop offs on either side.< /Review>

< Review>
Amazing hiking trail. Although it is near a busy street, but you can easily disappear and get lost in the small vista points or go down to the beach and immerse yourself. I would highly recommend it after windy or rainy period so you can see Catalina and the Channel Islands. Also a great place to watch for migrating whales</Review>

<userid>100465323874267776626< /userid><review>Really nice little walk along the cliffs. There's a steep ramp to go down to the beach. At low tide you can climb around and play on the rocks. The trail at the top is pretty flat and paved so anyone can do it. Highly recommend to come by in the early evening for sunset! Just keep in mind that it can get a little busy on nice days.</review>< pictures>

< Review>
One if Orange County's beautiful nature  areas. Beach below with trails through the high ground above looking out at a spectacular view of the ocean. One of the only places around that bicycles are allowed on the beach. Depending upon the time of year whales can be seen as the Grey Humpbacks migrate along the coast.< /Review>

<Rating>5</Rating>< Review>
Visited this beach on a late spring evening and got simply "wow"ed. The best part of the beach for me was the low traffic. The black rocks decorate the beach line very artistically. You pay $10 per car to get in and there's just one rest area at the south end of the lot. I wish they had some rest areas on the beach as well. Overall a great beach to take a stroll.< /Review>

One of my favorite beaches in Southern California. It's pretty level so you can walk for miles admiring the beautiful rock formations and cliffs. Parking is pricey @ $15 for the day but worth it.</text>

While there was no restaurant or bar due to Covid, the stay was absolutely fabulous. The renaissance vibe and overall decor are wonderful, the courtyard is a delight, the cleaning staff is very friendly and accommodating. The only complaint we had was that the bed was a bit soft. Other than that, it was wonderful to be there! And you cannot beat how accessible the location is from everywhere in the area!<//review>

Excellent hotel! It has easy access to the 405. Beautifully furnished. Large rooms. < Text>
I had a wonderful stay. I wish I could've stayed longer. The hotel is beautiful and well appointed. Parking is complimentary due to the pandemic, which was nice. The only thing is you have to insert the room key into the parking reader a couple of times before it reads it to open the lift gate, but nothing more serious than that. The room is beautiful and so comfortable. I would suggest they upgrade their t.v. system to larger t.v.'s (they only have 32 inches), and the ability to connect to streaming services like some other, more modern hotels. The front desk was so friendly and helpful. They offered the ice bucket at the front desk and I was able to call down and ask them to bring up a bottle corkscrew. Otherwise, it was a wonderful stay and I would absolutely stay here again.</Text>

<text>We booked this hotel through Hotels.com as it was conveniently located near the Airport and Manhattan Beach.

Our initial reception was fantastic - friendly check in representative who was welcoming and helpful.  The list of positives ends there.

When we got to the room (room 405) we discovered blood stains on bed sheets, comforter, and towels.  Not just one stain, multiple stains in multiple places (sheets, comforter, bath towels).  Talk about making your skin crawl. Of course our initial inclination was that the room had not been cleaned or sanitized, and we are in the middle of a freaking pandemic.

We immediately went downstairs and  asked another front desk representative to send housekeeping to change all the linens (sheets, comforter, bath towels) while we were at dinner.

We also asked to speak to the manager, he was no where to be found, but we were advised that he (Jairo) would call us to discuss the problem.

Needless to say, Jairo never called.

Upon our late return from dinner, we found the room exactly how we had found it earlier, blood stains on all the linens.

We went down to inform another front desk representative to let them know, at 12:45am, to be told that housekeeping has left for the day and that they didn't have anyone to change the sheets.

The midnight desk clerk again vehemently denied that blood stains on the linens were possible until I showed him the photos. After showing him photo after photo he agreed to change our room to room 454.  And again he promised that one of the mangers Jairo, or Jack Ellis, would contact us immediately in the morning.

Again, no manager reached out to us.

Room 454 looked fine, however just being on the same floor as the bloody room left me feeling uneasy and nauseous all night.

Next day, we informed the check out clerk of the same issue, asking to talk to a manager, to be told that there is no manager on duty.  She mentioned again that Jack Ellis is the one to speak with, she said he is the front desk manager, and would give us a call to remedy the situation but we haven't received the call yet.

This hotel make no attempts at customer service.

I realize that doing business during a pandemic is difficult, but the management at this hotel should be on premises to deal with customers concerns and complaints.  This is truly an unacceptable way to do business, or to treat your clientele.< /text>< Pictures>

<Time>1601510400000<//Time><text>Checked-into this hotel with the intention of using their pool, jacuzzi, and loved that it was central to the Manhattan Beach business district plus the beach. I needed to get away from my native San Francisco due to the quarantine mandates, plus it was central to LA so I was close enough to visit family. It seemed like a great idea and location. It was just me, late 20's female. Needless to say, the hotel itself looks great but their management was terrible. Not to mention the folk that frequent the hotel had more of a motel vibe than anything else. There were families that were extremely loud down some of the corridors, where in others it seemed like a brothel, if you know what I mean. Beware of shifty people that roam the property.  This was not the peaceful stay I was hoping for. They also shut down the pool and jacuzzi without letting anyone know. On my last day someone pulled the fire alarm. At check-in I was told that I could not stay at my original booked room due to "unexpected" construction. On my last day, I asked to speak to a manager where I was informed he had stepped-out and would call me back, never happened. They had the decency of comping me a mere $50. If you want a motel vibe stay here. The remodeling and look of the place is very deceptive. Not at all a boutique hotel. If you're looking for an affordable spot close to the business district, beware of the horrible management, unexpected changes, plus how loud it is. Personally, very disappointed.<//text>< rating>

< text>
I am so glad I decided to stay at Ayres for the 4 nights while visiting family in the South Bay! I was greeted/checked-in by Anaid, who was friendly and professional. I was pleasantly surprised to find out I didn't have to pay $15 parking per day, and she gave us a fun fact sheet about the beautiful pieces throughout the hotel. I especially loved the peace and quiet there. The entire staff were welcoming and the service was excellent! There's a beautiful courtyard area, a pool and jacuzzi (that weren't crowded,) making it easy to enjoy. The room was equipped with free WiFi, fridge and microwave which came in handy, especially since covid, we could bring food back to the room and "social distance" instead of eating at a restaurant. Overall the hotel gets a high score from me and I will definitely return when in Los Angeles!</text>

<user_id>111569035346011118684<//user_id><name>Joe Parsons< /name><Date>1582415525899<//Date><rate>4<//rate><text>The room was excellent, as was the overall "vibe of the hotel. The one minor quibble I'd offer is that the restaurant--which feels like a very nice high-end establishment--is not up to the obvious high standards of the hotel.

In particular, the quality of the breakfast experience was not what I would have expected. On Friday morning, when my two companions and I sat down in a nearly empty restaurant, the service was quite, shall we say, leisurely. We had to ask for coffee, and when my eggs arrived, they were overcooked and my order was not correct. Speaking as someone who has owned restaurants in the past, I know that properly cooking a breakfast order--especially eggs--requires a certain skill and finess. The eggs were over-cooked at too high a temperature so that the edges were browned. They were edible, but not of the quality I would have expected. I received one slice of lightly toasted dry sourdough (butter was in wrapped packets on the table) and no jelly.

The orders for the three of us arrived at the table at different times. This was similar to our service experience at dinner the night before--we all had the same entree, but they arrived at different times.

None of of these are deal-killers, but the rest of your establishment is so nice that I would have expected food service to be at the same level of quality.

Joe Parsons</text><pictures>None</pictures>< response>

<Name>REGINA T<//Name><date>1556837521080</date>< Rate>

<Text>If you are in Los Angeles and want to do the beach circuit, stay at the Ayres Hotel in Manhattan Beach. It looks much better on the inside than the outside. I hate that they put a gate in the parking area because it's too close to the street and causes congestion. The hotel is conveniently located off the 405 and 10 mins to the beach. Plus, Costco is directly across the street as well as other places to buy food. I've stayed here 6 years ago and the quality and service are still the same.

I would encourage people to sit and enjoy the courtyard and lobby area. It transports you back to old world Europe. The rooms have a microwave, mini fridge and plenty of counter space.

Stayed here one night for my birthday. Will come back again because it's like 10 mins from LAX. < Review>
What a beautiful place!  As you enter the Ayres Manhattan Beach Hotel, you see this grand, sweeping imperial staircase in the lobby.  The decor has a wonderful Old World European flair â€“ a large tapestry behind the lobby desk, high ceilings, handcrafted dark wood furniture, beautiful paintings and an inviting fireplace.
When I checked in, I was greeted by a friendly clerk. She explained the dual use of the card key: one, for room entry and two, a means to turn on the lights.  As I walked down the hall to my room, I was impressed by the historical framed photographs of Frank Ayres and the early days of land development in Los Angeles.  My room was quite spacious, beautifully furnished and quite comfortable.
Breakfast at the Matisse restaurant in the hotel is reasonably priced and quite good. Like the hotel, the restaurant reminds you of a European restaurant â€“ beautiful paintings, white tablecloths and peaceful atmosphere.
I do recommend the Ayres Hotel as a great place to stay.  The atmosphere is one of warmth, elegance and comfort.  For me it was such a pleasant change from the more modern furnished hotels Iâ€™ve stayed in.< /Review>

< Text>
Left today after a week of staying for covid exposure. (Was covid neg yay). They had rules already set for us, made evident on the day of arrival. All front desk and housekeeping wearing masks appropriately. It was nice knowing Ayres Hotel supports front line workers who have family at home they want to protect. I was able to get a hotel the day I found out about the exposure, which is superb service! There is a refrigerator and microwave so I brought all my food for the week and stayed in my room. Going to common areas is forbidden, for obvious reasons (though the lobby and outside courtyard are sooo elegant and cute). All you have to do at the end of your stay is collect all your dirty linens and throw it into a large trashbag and another trashbag for throwing out all your trash. Best way to keep housekeeping from getting exposed. Very very happy with my stay. Will come back after covid is over.< /Text>

Unlike a chain hotel, this feels more like having a room in an old mansion and everyone is waiting to gather in the parlor to play a murder mystery game. <user>110289354095517639516<//user><user_name>Joe Shields<//user_name><Date>1551333971394< /Date><Rate>2</Rate>< text>
It tries to be fancy, but it's just a normal hotel with a weird aesthetic and some very poorly designed features.

They have a power saving thing that you're supposed to put your room card into to turn on all the lights. The person I was staying with took his with him while I was in the shower... leaving me in total darkness. There's also omnipresent "classical" music playing on the first floor.

They also require you to use your room card to enter and exit the parking lot. The readers are poorly placed and usually require you to get out of your car. The entrances are on a busy street, so it's dangerous. Ever heard of parking passes and a towing service? I guess this place hasn't.< /text>

< Text>
The Ayres Hotel is a great upscale place to stay. The decor is fancy. The amenities are top notch. The staff is friendly. The lobby alone is a marvelous sight. There is an upscale restaurant attached as well.

Access to the hotel during heavy traffic is somewhat tricky. The main entrance on Hindry Avenue is also the access ramp to the I-405 freeway, so it gets combative when trying to turn left across traffic. The secondary entrance is on Rosecrans Avenue, which is heavily congested at times.</Text>

< text>
This is the very best place to stay when in LA, for a number of reasons.

1. Very close proximity to the airport, without the noise.
2.THE best and most comfy pillows and beds I've found in a hotel.
3. Beautiful surroundings. Makes one feel like you're living in a castle!
4. The restaurant attached to the hotel is excellent both in service and food. You don't need to drive in traffic to get a great dining experience.
5. Rooms are lovely, quiet, and equipped with a refrigerator and nice, separate, bathroom area.

In all, an excellent experience and the only place I'll stay when traveling to LA on business or pleasure.
Thank you!
Kathryn Clayton</text>

<userid>114670773567409363259</userid>< Pictures>
None</Pictures>
< review>
The Ayres Manhattan Beach was a very nice looking hotel. The entryway and lobby are tastefully decorated in Victorian style. You'll want to take pictures. Although Victorian is their theme, the hotel could stand some modernization. The appliances and TV are dated, and the shower has an incredibly impractical shower head that ends up getting the bathroom floor wet. That being said, the staff are friendly, and the pool is nice, if a bit small. Beautiful chandeliers on the interior along beautiful banquet rooms make me feel this would be a great wedding venue. In our particular room the sink countertop was clearly broken at some point and poorly put back together, but fully functional. The windows don't have full privacy, because only the slightly transparent curtains pull fully shut. The lot behind our room was private with thick hedges, but fully closing curtains would still be nice. Parking is easy and only $10/night, which is a steal for the area. Rooms were very spacious, clean, and the furniture was high quality. The mattress was super comfortable. It was also very quiet; no noise could be heard in the hallway or other rooms. All-in-all, it's a nice hotel that needs a few updates to be truly great, but for the price, I feel it was a good value.</review>

< review>
This place was a treasured find.  A friend was getting married, and the reception was here.  We decided to come early and stay four nights total, and I am so glad we did.  They shuttle to the beach, the restaurant on site was good for all meals (we went a few times during our stay), and the rooms were gorgeous!  We arrived very early, and even though we were supposed to check in at 3 they let us check in at 11:30 when they had a room available.  After waking up at 3am Pacific time, that was very much appreciated.  At the end of our stay, we left our electronics bag there when leaving for the airport, and they had it packaged up and sent to us very quickly.  Nothing like leaving in an Uber at 4:30 am only to realize your tablet, keyboard, mouse, and countless charger cables were all left in the hotel lobby.  It was a huge relief when they found it, and let us know it was no problem to mail it to us.  Lori helped us through it all, along with others on staff.  All were very professional and helpful.  When I come back to LA, I'm staying with Ayres.</review>

Everywhere you look around the hotel, you have created a delight to your guests' senses.  It is exquisite, yet casually comfortable, with the evening-lit inner courtyard, the expansive upper level balcony, the lobby fireplace that is tall enough to stand in, the curved iron staircase that leads to the second level, the peaceful and beautiful library room, which is one of my favorite places at Hawthorne. I look forward to another stay with you for our next conference in the Spring.

Sherie Smith

< review>
The rooms were beautiful and huge.  Clean and functional.  But the first room had no working heating or cooling.  The man at the front desk wanted me to solve the problem as he kept asking lots of questions, like What kind of heater did it have?  Did it have a thermostat on the wall?  Etc.  Etc.  He did offer to bring up my bags which I appreciated.  When he came in my room, he determined the heater-cooler was not working.  He offered to change my room.  I agreed if he could get me closer to the elevator.  He did but I could not figure out how to get heat in the room, only cool.  So I put on my pajamas and got under the covers.  I did not want to move again.  The last day a nice man working on the wall near the elevator turned the heat on and the room felt wonder-ful for the last hour.< /review>

< Text>
A decent hotel, with mostly large, airy rooms. Windows open, at least a bit. Some top floor rooms are noisy due to mechanical equipment on the roof. Courtyard facing rooms may be noisy if they have an event going on, or if there are noisy kids in the pool. Highway facing rooms are not suitable if you want to have a window open, they are ok with air conditioning on.< /Text>

< Review>
We were surprised, in a good way, at how the Ayres met our needs for an overnight near LAX. It was so much less than other nearby hotels, and it offered a certain serenity that was most welcome on the last day of our trip to Southern California. There is something about a hotel that does NOT offer free breakfast that keeps the sports teams, clubs, and droves away, and although we love kids, we needed a respite. Matisse provided us with a relaxing and very well prepared lunch, and the room facing the courtyard was quiet, clean and comfortable.</Review>

<Rating>1<//Rating><GmapID>0x80c2b417a15779c7:0xd18227ecdffd65aa</GmapID>< Review>
THIS IS A LONG ONE... BRACE YOURSELVES.
My husband and I decided to celebrate our WEDDING anniversary at the Matisse Restaurant, inside of the Ayres hotel. We had a few family members join us (we did not want to do anything too extravagant) for the evening. Upon arrival, the vibe was a bit callous (RED FLAG #1), however, I did not want to jump to any conclusions regarding my opinion of the place (and it was too late to go anywhere else) so we stayed to try and enjoy our evening. After ordering and eating our food, I found that it was not spectacular (could have been better for the price), but not too bad. The service was so-so (although the waiter was friendly so I am not including him in this bad rating). After being there a couple hours, we were done and gearing up to pay the tab. As we waited for the check, there was one incident where, the host made it her point to single out, speak to, and play with ONE CHILD in particular. While ignoring the other FOUR children who were in attendance. The first time she did it, I did not say anything, but after she came back 3 times to address the same child (the lightest child at the table). I had to bring it to her attention that, the other children even tried to speak to her and she ignored them yet she continues to play with and compliment this ONE. Even after I brought this it to her attention; instead of addressing the other children, she still ignored them and said "Oh... I didn't see them" then she added insult to injury by going back to the mixed-race child and offering him a dessert (and we had a cake!). She did not offer any of the other children anything. That was RED FLAG #2.
Then my niece had to use the restroom so my sister went to ask the front desk clerk (of the hotel) where the restrooms were... the clerk frowned at her and SNARLED "it's over there" while pointing in the distance to a long hall. My sister did not say anything, she just came back into the restaurant to tell me what happened. The Chicano waiter who then informed us where is was. The host then stated "there is no way to find the restroom without someone showing you were to go". I then informed her of how the front-desk clerk behaved and how she basically shooed my sister and niece off and she stated that she would "do something about it". After we finished, everyone moved towards the lobby. As we were leaving, there was a group of teenagers who were coming into the lobby from outside, they were loud and playing around and no one blinked an eye. My 4 year old niece, 10 year old niece and 9 year old nephew were telling jokes and laughing as they waited for everyone to gather in the lobby. The same clerk who snarled at my sister, called security on them. As I walked into the lobby, I saw her roll her eyes, heard her exhale as if she was annoyed, and saw her stare angrily at these CHILDREN as she picked up a two-way radio and called the security (or her manager). The manager came out of the back room and appeared to tell her, he was not going to do anything because they were children and they were not doing anything wrong. At this point, I was appalled and insulted. I went to inform the host (because I was told she was the manager over the hotel/restaurant staff). She informed me that she had nothing to do with the front desk and that she would introduce me to the supervisor and he could handle the complaint. I went to put my things inside of the car and to take the children out of the lobby. Upon my return, I noticed that the angry clerk was ducking off to the back and the supervisor was now tending to the front desk. I asked for the name of the angry clerk and they would not give it to me. I was told that they would "take care of the situation", but I think they did nothing. This is the treatment my family and I received, on my anniversary, after spending a pretty penny with this establishment. I am disappointed and will not be returning to this place. I will also advise anyone not to come here. Save your time, money, and feelings and go some place where they APPRECIATE ALL of their CUSTOMERS.<//Review>

We stayed here because we were going to a concert at the Forum.  The hotel was very nice and much more than we expected for the area.  The rooms were nice and beds comfy.  The ambiance was great!  Staff was very friendly and we enjoy the outdoor verandas over looking the pool area.  Would definitely recommend this hotel as one of the nicest places to stay close to the Forum.  Lots of good restaurants in the area.  We had dinner at Flemmings that was right down the street.< /review>

<rate>4</rate><Resp>None</Resp><pictures>None<//pictures>< review>
I've driven by this place twice a day for nearly 18 months and finally went inside for lunch. Based on the location, I always assumed that this was a glorified Motel 6. Boy was I wrong!

Inside, the hotel looks like an Italian villa complete with tapestries, elaborate paintings and floor tiles. The food in the restaurant was superb (albeit hotel prices). If you need to stay in the South Bay for business, this appears to be a fantastic option.

Star deduction because the parking rates are ridiculous. Park across the street at Costco instead.</review>

< Text>
My family stayed here during our time of mourning after losing my aunt. We needed someplace near all the services to be together and I am very glad we selected the Ayres hotel.

Only snafu happened upon check-in for my mom and sister, as my fiance and I were paying for both rooms and the person at the front desk at the time told them that wasn't allowed. After getting a manager involved, we were able to move beyond and my mom and sister were able to check in.

Once we arrived, we were very impressed with the lobby and design of the interior. Simply gorgeous!

Our room was big and the bed was cozy.

The parking lot is an absolute mess with the system in place, but we managed to navigate anyway.

Overall, this is a gorgeous hotel with courteous staff on duty who greeted us every time we'd come back into the hotel.< /Text>

<resp>None<//resp><Text>Most all was really great - loved the room and the hotel itself.  A couple of issues which prevents me from a perfect score on our stay. Parking was a good value at $10/day knowing I had a place to park and lot was somewhat secured was great.  The card system getting out of the lot was not good, I had to get out of the car each time and insert the card to exit for some reason.  Staff were courteous and professional however housekeeping missed our room one day even though we were out all day, and I another day they didn't replenish some of the supplies.  I asked the front desk to provide the supplies and they said they would  but we didn't get the needed supplies.  Pool is small. The restaurant - Matisse - was excellent - a bit pricey for dinner, but great for breakfast.  The restaurant staff were great and made us feel like we were VIPs.  Overall I would highly recommend this hotel as the minor issues we had are tweaks that can be made in your operations. The facilities are beautiful and clean. The staff was very courteous and willing to help. The biggest drawbacks are 1) the workout facility gets too hot in the morning with the sun pouring in. 2) the breakfast options are nice, but not great (why have a quesadilla without salsa?); especially for the price. 3) Location... although it is a good spot for travelers to LAX, I try to avoid Los Angeles like the plague (so I unfortunately don't see myself returning for that reason alone; but if you build elsewhere, I would look you up). 5<//Rate>
<text>We were a party of four, staying at the hotel for two nights, predominately so we could attend a ELO concert at the Forum in Inglewood on Saturday night. We flew in from Sydney Australia on the Friday and flew home again on Sunday evening.

I booked two rooms at the hotel because of my excellent experience at another Ayres property in Anaheim around five years ago and because of its proximity to the concert venue.

We were not disappointed and I would recommend this hotel above all the others I have stayed at, in the LAX and Manhattan Beach areas.

The staff are professional, accommodating and look after their guests. The hotel itself is beautifully presented and the meals we ate there were lovely. The beds are incredibly comfortable and we found the hotel to be quiet.

There are a number of chain restaurants in the area, a Costco and good access to LA's freeways. Its a short drive or Uber to the close by communities, at Manhattan, Hermosa and Redondo beaches, where you can swim, ride a bike along the foreshore and take your pick from umpteen other restaurants. The hotel also runs a shuttle to Manhattan Beach.

Do yourself a favor and stay here, we enjoyed our stay very much and left with such a positive impression of the hotel and its staff.</text>< pics>
None<//pics>

<UserId.>114589035609607635319<//UserId.><Time>1437156878272<//Time>< Text>
We stayed here a few years ago for a family reunion and it was wonderful! So for a family vacation for 5 days we decided to return. Well, this time, not as great. No free breakfast anymore and $10 to park with annoying gates that rarely worked, much less  if you could even pull close enough to insert the key card. I could understand the parking fee if you were boxed in by other businesses that used your parking lot. But I don't think you have overflow parking being on a corner, car dealership nearby and a gas station on the other corner. Parking was never an issue in the past nor was it this visit so the parking fee in my opinion is just like the airlines anymore, just one more way to price gouge a traveler. The view we had was horrible, granted the homeless tent on the other side of the fence isn't your property or your problem, but when paying $1047 for 5 days, it is my problem when I have to keep the drapes closed to avoid looking at it. The shower situation is ridiculous too. I normally take a shower in under 7 minutes. I don't think a shower that barely spits water out is saving any water when you have to stay in there over 20 minutes to wash oneself and get the shampoo and then conditioner out of your hair.  On the up side, you do have a very friendly staff, clean rooms and no complaints with housekeeping. This particular property I would not recommend to any of my family again, and for that I'm sad to say because we all enjoyed it so much before.</Text>

< review>
I will NEVER stay at your chain again.  We have been staying with Ayers for about 7 years.  My husband called to get reservations at this facility and even after they asked if we had stayed with them before no one mentioned anything about the parking situation or the buffet breakfast not included any longer.  We can stay for free at the Westin properties, but my husband chose Ayers for the last 7 years for the free parking and the included buffet breakfast.  When we arrived we we confronted with several gates, so we chose the one that led to the main lobby.  Mistake #1.  When we tried to leave in separate cars, we were delivering my daughter's 18th birthday new car to her at the university, I got out in 9 tries with the room card and my husband couldn't get out to follow me to the school.  He was there for about 8 minutes yelling at the intercom to get out cause he needed to follow me. AND when you go left in the parking lot toward the main lobby, you can only get out of the parking lot about three spots back off the traffic signal or spend 10 minutes making u turns to get onto the 405.  I figured since you are charging for parking now that you are also charging for the breakfast.  I called the front desk and asked if you were charging for breakfast and the person said yes and I asked how much and she simply said "it depends",  What the heck does that even mean?  My husband and I are extremely disappointed in this place.  He thinks the parents are gone now and it's the kids running it into the ground from greed.<//review>

<user_name>Dave Aronson<//user_name>< rate>
5<//rate>
< Text>
Overall excellent.  Clean, quiet, comfortable, not too expensive.  Located within walking distance of good facilities of assorted kinds, like restaurants, Starbucks, Staples, Costco (I hear the hotel will lend you a membership card), etc.  Very nice lobby area for sitting around in and chatting.  Surprisingly stable and fast WiFi.  Good restaurant, with a good variety of food, some rather interesting (especially the dinner "share plates"), and not *too* expensive.

The only thing I would ding them on that is under their control is that it seems like nobody reads the email.  If you register online, you get an email saying to reply to it if you have any questions or concerns or changes, but if you do, nobody replies.  I had asked a couple days in advance about transportation from the airport and tried to arrange early checkin... twice... nada.

The other downside, that's *not* their fault, is apparently a problem with the LA area in general.  If want to go anywhere not in walking distance and you don't have a car, you're screwed, because the public transit is horrible.  If you DO have a car, you're *still* screwed, because everybody and their dog are also driving and clogging up the roads!  The solution we found for this is Uber, which we really like.  (Except some of their political stands, but that's another review.)  However, if you're going to go more than a few trips or about 50 miles per day, strongly consider renting a car.  Just be aware that the hotel will also make you pay for parking, and their gate system to get in and out seems like a pain.< /Text>

(Translated by Google) The hotel is well located near Manhattan Beach, about 15 minutes by car without traffic and the area is not as ugly as the one near the airport.

We had problems: the first day, we checked early but there was no room, we consigned the suitcase and when we arrived at night we did not have a room, after 45 minutes of waiting they gave us one below what we contracted and the next day they promised us move to a suite, but it was not.

The last day, after arriving at night, they had not made the room and after protesting twice, they made the bed.

As compensation, they have discounted the price of one night. Therefore, bittersweet taste, the hotel is fine and spacious, but maybe we were unlucky.

(Original)
El hotel esta bien localizado cerca de Manhattan Beach, en coche como a 15 minutos sin trafico y la zona no es tan fea como la cercana al aeropuerto.
